# Global Audit Memory

## Scope Touched
- `contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol` — dominant audit focus; core risk surface is liquidity provision/withdrawal, LP share accounting, reward-debt tracking, and orderbook transfer/receive hooks that affect pool balances
- `contracts/interfaces/IGradientMarketMakerPool.sol` — interface surface reviewed mainly to confirm pool accounting expectations and externally visible state transitions
- `contracts/interfaces/IGradientRegistry.sol`, `contracts/interfaces/IUniswapV2Pair.sol`, `contracts/interfaces/IUniswapV2Router.sol` — supporting context for external pricing, registry wiring, and reserve-dependent deposit behavior
- Deposit/withdraw/reward flows — repeatedly identified as the main place where accounting units, pricing inputs, and actual received assets can diverge

## Issue Directions Seen
- Mismatch between reward accounting and LP share accounting, especially when deposit amounts and minted shares use different units or formulas
- LP share mint/burn logic appears sensitive to raw asset sums rather than economically consistent pool-value accounting
- Deposit sizing depends on external Uniswap spot reserves, creating a recurring manipulation/pricing direction
- Fee-on-transfer or deflationary token behavior is a persistent direction because credited amounts may exceed assets actually received
- Orderbook inflow/outflow hooks remain relevant to pool invariant drift, though less developed than the main accounting findings
- Slippage-check behavior was examined but has not remained a core cross-round direction

## Useful Context
- The audit has concentrated much more on `GradientMarketMakerPool` than on surrounding files; interfaces and helper/admin areas have been secondary context rather than primary issue sources
- Durable concern pattern: the contract mixes multiple accounting notions at once — nominal deposit inputs, actual transferred balances, LP shares, reward debt, and externally sourced reserve prices
- Cross-round signal so far favors high-severity accounting/pricing faults over governance or emergency-control issues
- Underexplored areas are mostly peripheral sections and interface-adjacent behavior; the strongest accumulated evidence remains in the pool’s core liquidity and reward paths
